<TITLE> Unassuming Ford steps into the spotlight again </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, June 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - South African Graham Ford's reputation as a behind-the-scenes motivator will be put to a big test after he was named India's new cricket coach. The 46-year-old former South Africa coach was chosen by the Indian board's coaching committee on Saturday to take over the post which fell vacant after the outspoken Greg Chappell quit. The former Australia skipper ended his two-year term in April following the team's shock first round exit at the World Cup dismayed millions of passionate India fans and left the team in turmoil. Ford, currently cricket director of English county Kent, edged out former England off-spinner John Emburey after the Indian board had rejected on Wednesday the candidature of Australian Dav Whatmore, the early front-runner. He guided South Africa to eight wins from 11 test series in two years until he was axed in 2001 after back-to-back series defeats against Australia during troubled times in the wake of the Hansie Cronje match-fixing saga. Ford earned respect as a motivator while staying in the background as coach of Natal and then South Africa, a skill that would be crucial to succeed in a frenzied Indian atmosphere. He coached stalwarts like Jonty Rhodes, Shaun Pollock and Lance Klusener for both club and country. The India job provides him with a fresh opportunity to return to international cricket. Indian fans will hope it is a new beginning, free of the controversies that dogged the Chappell er
